Issues.Body:
* fixes prodmode issue in integration/bazel

BREAKING CHANGE:

@bazel/typescript is now a peerDependency of @angular/bazel so user's of @angular/bazel must add @bazel/typescript to their package.json

This is related to https://github.com/angular/angular/issues/29454 so please read that first for more context.

To use angular and angular libraries from npm we must currently run `ngc` on them in `postinstall` step of yarn or npm.

```
  "scripts": {
    "postinstall": "ngc -p ./angular-metadata.tsconfig.json"
  }
```

This generates `.ngfactory.js` files that we can then use as inputs to Bazel rules that require them. The generated `.ngfactory.js` files need to work with a number rules in the typical use cases. They need to be compatible with the `rollup_bundle` rule in order to produce a production bundle. They also need to be valid inputs to `ts_devserver` and `ts_web_test_suite` which require named UMD or named AMD. The postinstall step also generated `.ngsummary.js` files to use in JIT mode with `ts_web_test_suite` (`"angularCompilerOptions": { "enableSummariesForJit": true }` must be set in `angular-metadata.tsconfig.json` to generate these outputs).

`ngc` is able to produce both `umd` and `amd` outputs depending on the configuration in `angular-metadata.tsconfig.json`. `ngc` is just a wrapper around `tsc` which controls the output format.

## UMD format

With the following in `angular-metadata.tsconfig.json`,

```
  "compilerOptions": {
    ...
    "module": "umd",
    "moduleResolution": "node",
  },
```

`tsc` generates UMD in the *simplified CommonJS wrapper format* where `require` is passed through to the factory function:

```
(function (factory) {
    if (typeof module === "object" && typeof module.exports === "object") {
        var v = factory(require, exports); if (v !== undefined) module.exports = v;
    }
    else if (typeof define === "function" && define.amd) {
        define(["require", "exports", "./mod"], factory);
    }
})(function (require, exports) {
    var mod_1 = require("./mod");
    exports.t = mod_1.something + 1;
});
```

Some documentation on this format incase you are not familiar with it:

* https://requirejs.org/docs/api.html#cjsmodule
* https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/handbook/modules.html (scroll down to Code Generation for Modules)
* https://github.com/requirejs/requirejs/wiki/Differences-between-the-simplified-CommonJS-wrapper-and-standard-AMD-define

