This AMD format works with `ts_devserver` and `ts_web_test_suite` which both use RequireJS as the loader. `rollup-plugin-commonjs` can't handle this format but there is another rollup plugin `rollup-plugin-amd` which can. This plugin needs to be added to `rollup_bundle` to handle these files as inputs: https://github.com/bazelbuild/rules_nodejs/pull/625.

By default, however, `rollup-plugin-amd` converts the AMD to ES6 using default import statements (`import foo from './foo'`) while the `tsc` generated amd format assumes its es6 import equivalents are namespaces imports (`import * as foo from './foo'`). In order to get `rollup-plugin-amd` to work with this file, a postinstall patch is needed to the `@buxlabs/amd-to-es6` npm library used by `rollup-plugin-amd`:

```
log('\n# patch: @buxlabs/amd-to-es6 to generate namespace imports instead of default imports');
sed('-i', 'ImportDefaultSpecifier', 'ImportNamespaceSpecifier',
    'node_modules/@buxlabs/amd-to-es6/src/lib/getImportDeclaration.js');
```

also, adding `rollup-plugin-amd` to rollup_bundle means that some UMD formats will now fail to bundle as the plugin will try to convert the `define` within the UMD format. Because of this we limit this plugin to work on `.ngfactory.js` so that other files that may be UMD don't break the bundle.

`internal/rollup/rollup.config.js`:
```
    amd({
      include: '**/*.ngfactory.js',
    }),
```

Using the `tsc` AMD format with the patched `rollup-plugin-amd` added to `rollup_bundle` we can generate `.ngfactory` files which work for devmode (`ts_devserver` and `ts_web_test_suite`) and prodmod (`rollup_bundle`).

